<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Free Postage Exchanged for Profile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The latest freebie being dangled before Internet  
users to coax them to share their personal information for a 
database: postage. 
</P>
<P>
	A South Florida company is giving away first-class, postage-paid  
envelopes to anyone willing to fill out an online application 
including questions on household income, education level, date of 
birth and what kind of car they drive. The survey is used to build 
a profile that will allow sponsors to target advertising and 
coupons on those envelopes based on that person's tastes or 
perceived needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Postage4Free.com Inc., a six-person operation founded this year,  
kicks off its Web site today. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers who complete the online application receive 10  
business-sized envelopes, each with a first-class 33-cent stamp, in 
the mail in four to six weeks, said Marisa Dottori, who co-founded 
the company. Customers can come back for reorders after three 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The envelopes are sponsored by advertisers who get space for  
their pitch on the on the envelope or pay to have tear-off coupons 
attached to the back, Dottori said. The coupons are expected to be 
more lucrative because they target customers based on a profile, 
Dottori said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects millions of customers within six months,  
said Dottori. She said that assessment is based on an estimated 150 
million American Internet users and the fact the U.S. Postal 
Service delivers more than 107 billion pieces of first-class mail 
per year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dottori won't reveal the names of her company's advertising  
sponsors until after the first mailing. However, she said they 
include pizza, soft drink, cereal and video companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Dottori also declined to reveal advertising rates but said the  
tear-off coupons will be the priciest. ``For example, we know 
specifically that that person has a dog in their home so that's 
going to be a higher cost per thousand,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving away free stuff on the Internet is not new and has become  
big business. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred by intense competition for Web surfers, the occasional  
come-on of a few years ago has exploded into a widespread 
commercial strategy -- key to drawing visitors to Internet sites, 
drawing advertisers who want to capture that audience and getting 
online businesses off the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not just software and e-mail services. Like winners of a  
giant shopping spree, consumers can find items in Web categories 
stretching from technology to entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	Though figures on total Internet freebies were not available, a  
recent search looking for ``free'' and ``giveaway'' on the search 
engine AltaVista reveals more than 1,140,000 Web pages with both 
words. 
</P>
<P>
	The catch is that many of the free sites and services require  
bargain hunters to look at advertisements, give up personal 
information to marketers, or buy related products. 
</P>
<P>
	Products include music downloads, pornography and videos. There  
are desktop themes to jazz up any computer screen, animated 
greeting cards and a missing-person people finder. There are even 
free jokes. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing I've learned is that 'freebie' speaks louder to the  
consumer than anything,'' said David Marcus, CEO of Houseit.com, a 
Web site management company, an advertiser with Postage4Free.com. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
