<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady, Giuliani in Money Chase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Neither Hillary Rodham Clinton nor Rudolph  
Giuliani is an official candidate, but both are deep into the money 
chase as they explore possible races for the U.S. Senate from New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Mrs. Clinton, the Democrat, and Giuliani, the Republican,  
are considered prodigious fund-raisers. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady has amply demonstrated her fund-raising ability  
in recent years, crisscrossing the country to help fellow Democrats 
-- and her husband -- fill campaign coffers. She is taking time out 
from a two-week family vacation to work the money circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani, the Republican mayor of New York, also has proven his  
ability to rake in the campaign cash. From April, when he formed 
his Senate exploratory committee, through June 30, the mayor 
reported raising $2.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who formed her exploratory committee on July 6,  
does not have to make a report to the Federal Election Commission 
until later in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	But from the events Mrs. Clinton already has held or has  
scheduled over the next couple of weeks, spokesman Howard Wolfson 
estimates a take of about $1.5 million. ``It's going very well,'' 
he said confidently. 
</P>
<P>
	Six fund-raising events in Massachusetts and New York during the  
Clintons' two-week vacation are expected to rake in more than 
$600,000 for the first lady's Senate exploratory committee. A 
two-day trip to Texas for five fund-raising events just before the 
vacation netted Mrs. Clinton about $500,000, according to Wolfson. 
Four events held earlier in New York and Washington took in about 
$400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fund-raising totals do not include money raised from a  
direct-mail campaign, personal telephone calls she has made and 
unsolicited donations. Wolfson said he did not know how much those 
efforts had netted. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady's fund-raising team has set a goal of $25 million  
for the race and Wolfson said he believes the target is well within 
reach. 
</P>
<P>
	New York's statewide races have become increasingly expensive.  
In last year's Senate race, the Republican incumbent Alfonse 
D'Amato spent more than $20 million in his losing bid for a fourth 
term. Democratic winner Charles Schumer spent more than $15 
million. Republican George Pataki spent more than $20 million last 
year in winning a second term as governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the Clinton fund-raising prowess, Republicans and  
anti-Clinton conservatives are rallying their own troops. 
</P>
<P>
	New York GOP Chairman William Powers has launched a new Internet  
site specifically aimed at raising money to help finance 
anti-Hillary Clinton work. Other GOP state committees across the 
country have begun fund-raising efforts based on Mrs. Clinton's 
expected candidacy in New York. All or part of the money raised 
from those campaigns is to be filtered into New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, in early June, conservative radio talk show host Gary  
Nolan and veteran conservative strategist Craig Shirley announced a 
national drive to ``stop Hillary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to raise $10 million,'' Nolan said, vowing that all of  
the money raised by Conservatives for Effective Leadership will be 
spent in an effort to defeat Mrs. Clinton in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A letter from Nolan to 40,000 potential contributors warned that  
``the liberals want Hillary to be president,'' claimed she and her 
husband were corrupt and that ``she's a committed radical Marxist 
to boot!'' 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the first lady sent a fund-raising letter of her own to  
about 1 million potential donors noting that ``you and I have been 
through a lot together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope you will help me launch this effort by sending as  
generous a financial donation as you can afford,'' she wrote. 
``Together, I believe we can accomplish great things, for our 
families, for New York, and for our nation.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
