<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Event Protesters Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Ten people detained by police for staging  
a political protest during the opening ceremony of the World 
Athletics Championships were freed without charges Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The breach of security at the Seville stadium was condemned by  
the national news media and politicians, who noted that the 
incident came at the same time the southern Andalusian city is 
bidding for the 2008 summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocates of transferring ETA Basque prisoners from jails around  
Spain to cells closer to home, the intruders easily slipped into 
the stadium Friday night on regular tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of them, dressed as oversized official mascots with signs  
urging repatriation of the prisoners joined singers and the master 
of ceremonies on stage for 20 minutes before being dragged away by 
guards. 
</P>
<P>
	Other members of the group, admitted with knapsacks unveiled  
banners with the same propaganda and ropes. 
</P>
<P>
	Their protest was in full view of TV cameras and thousands of  
spectators at the 60,000-seat stadium, including Prince Felipe, son 
of King Juan Carlos and heir to the Spanish crown. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven men and three women, ranging in age from 22 to 34,  
were accused of public disorder and spent the weekend in detention. 
Police claimed one of them was the brother of an ETA leader who 
once headed the Madrid commando. 
</P>
<P>
	Seville Court Judge Auxiliadora Echevarria ordered their release  
Sunday morning after questioning them most of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers representing the accused insisted they were not  
affiliated with ETA but were peaceful advocates of ETA demands that 
some 500 commandos jailed around Spain be moved to prisons in the 
Basque region. 
</P>
<P>
	The armed separatist group, which has killed nearly 800 people  
in its 31-year campaign for independence for the northern Basque 
land, declared a unilateral cease-fire nearly a year ago and 
recently entered talks with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident received front page headlines in Madrid newspapers  
and editorial condemnation of the lax security at the 
championships. The main opposition Socialist Party demanded an 
explanation from Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's top police commander, Juan Cotino, admitted  
``there was a failure on part of the organizers and also the 
security forces, which ought to have responded before the event 
took place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	El Mundo, a nationally distributed major daily published in  
Madrid, reported that the ticketed advocates managed to pass 
through three layers of security. One of the false mascots, ordered 
at the gate to remove his smiling costume head, complied but was 
allowed inside after genially observing how hot it was inside the 
inflated outfit, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	El Mundo noted that police blamed the organizers, who in turn  
blamed security forces, while politicians criticized their 
opponents in government. The newspaper urged a complete 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Security was tighter after the incident, even requiring  
spectators to open bottles of water before passing through the 
gates to insure they did not contain combustible liquids. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
