<DOCNO> APW19990822.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Scott Zolak was one of Bill Parcells' favorite players in New  
England, but the Jets coach had little patience with the reserve 
quarterback and waived him on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came two days after Parcells traded a conditional draft  
pick to Green Bay for Rick Mirer. 
</P>
<P>
	Zolak, a nine-year veteran in his first year with the Jets,  
played poorly in Friday's 10-9 exhibition win over the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a better opportunity for him to let him go now,''  
Parcells said of Zolak, 10-of-22 for 90 yards against Philadelphia. 
The former Patriots backup had signed a one-year, $400,000 deal 
with the Jets in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer, a former first-round draft pick of the Seahawks, is with  
his fourth team in as many years. Parcells passed on Mirer, who is 
expected to make his Jets' debut Saturday against the Giants, in 
favor of Drew Bledsoe in the 1993 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer hasn't taken a regular season snap since 1997, when he  
started three games for the Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	``First of all, he has fairly good movement,'' Parcells said of  
Mirer. ``He can move around a little bit. I think at this stage 
he's been exposed -- this is his fourth pro system -- and he's going 
to have a good idea what's going on from a football standpoint. I 
know he's a good worker, a good preparer, those kinds of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Bengals    	
</P>
<P>
	Safety Kelvin Moore was in stable condition at a hospital in  
Pontiac, Mich., two days after he broke a vertebra in his neck 
while making a tackle in an exhibition game against the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore has feeling in his arms and legs and is expected to make  
``an excellent recovery,'' team Dr. Robert Heidt Jr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching film of the play, coach Bruce Coslet said Moore  
did everything right and still got hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked like he was a little bit stumbling into him and just  
bent his head back,'' Coslet said. ``It just happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Panthers    	
</P>
<P>
	Two days after getting solid performances from Steve Beuerlein,  
Jeff Lewis and Dameyune Craig, first-year Panthers coach George 
Seifert wasn't interested in talking about the status of the three 
quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to reveal whether incumbent starter Beuerlein would  
work with the first-team offense in the Panthers' next exhibition 
Friday night in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we've arrived and we've got all this exotic Pro  
Bowl-caliber depth now,'' he said. ``We're just kind of giving them 
an opportunity to show us what they've got, and it was good. They 
took advantage of their shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	The hamstring injury that cornerback Jason Sehorn sustained a  
week before training camp continues to heal slowly and he will miss 
another week or two, according to coach Jim Fassel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn had an MRI on Friday and doctors decided not to let him  
run this week, Fassel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although he is just striding and things, they just want to  
make sure he completely rests it,'' Fassel said. ``So we are going 
to take him off the running.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *Bills    	
</P>
<P>
	Backup nose tackle Pat Williams craves playing time, but this  
time the Bills gave him more than he asked for. 
</P>
<P>
	All-Pro Ted Washington stayed home after a house fire and  
Williams had four tackles in the Bills' 20-19 exhibition loss to 
the Redskins on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was on the field for about all but 10 of the Redskins'  
74 plays. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	When Terry Glenn is healthy, New England's offense is one of the  
best in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	After setting a rookie record with 90 receptions, Glenn has been  
hampered by injuries. Last year, the receiver missed four games 
with a pulled hamstring. He returned for the next three before 
breaking his ankle against the Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	But Glenn had five receptions for 85 yards and a touchdown in  
New England's 34-14 victory over Dallas on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	Miami's biggest goal in training camp was to upgrade an offense  
that ranked 16th in the NFL last year. Midway through the 
exhibition schedule, there's scant evidence of progress. 
</P>
<P>
	The first team failed to produce a first down in the exhibition  
opener against New Orleans, and in Saturday night's 13-10 victory 
at San Diego, Miami managed just one touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	It didn't take long for Edgerrin James to make an impact for  
Indianapolis. The rookie, playing in the first half, rushed for 77 
yards on 10 carries and scored on runs of 16 yards and 12 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Edgerrin really showed why we picked him so high,'' Colts  
coach Jim Mora said. ``He gave us a spark and showed what he can 
do. He looks like the real deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts took James as the fourth overall draft pick, one spot  
ahead of New Orleans who took Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990822.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 17:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mutiny 2, Crew 1, SO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Pete Marino, Josh Keller and Steve Ralston  
scored in the shootout as the Tampa Bay Mutiny defeated the 
Columbus Crew 2-1 Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second shooutout victory for Tampa Bay in Columbus  
this year. The Mutiny won 1-0 at Crew Stadium on May 22. The Crew 
won the only game between the two in Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory gave the Mutiny (11-14) sole possession of third  
place in the MLS' Eastern Conference. The Crew (15-9) remained in 
second. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian McBride of Columbus opened the scoring in the 38th minute  
with his first goal since April 3. Robert Warzycha sent a pass to 
McBride, who got a shot off his right foot and inside the right 
post past Mutiny goalkeeper Scott Garlick. 
</P>
<P>
	Raul Diaz Arce tied the score with a penalty kick in the 64th  
minute after Marino was hauled down by Warzycha. 
</P>
<P>
	McBride missed the Crew's first attempt in the shootout and  
teammate Stern John scored, but the goal came after time had 
expired. Garlick then saved a shot by Billy Thompson to clinch the 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Crew led 17-14 in total shots and 6-3 in shots on goal.  
Garlick had five saves, while Crew goalkeeper Mark Dougherty 
stopped two shots. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
