<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants CB Sehorn Still Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- The hamstring injury that New York  
Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn sustained a week before training 
camp continues to heal slowly and he will miss another week or two, 
coach Jim Fassel said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn had an MRI on Friday and doctors decided not to let him  
run this week, Fassel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although he is just striding and things, they just want to  
make sure he completely rests it,'' Fassel said in a conference 
call. ``So we are going to take him off the running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn has spent most of training camp working with trainers  
while the team practiced. This past week, he has been doing agility 
drills, mostly running around cones and jumping side to side over 
prone tackling pads. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he kind of pulled a little scar tissue, which is not  
bad,'' Fassel said. ``But it can give him a sensation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the MRI showed no problems, Fassel said the team is going  
to be cautious with Sehorn, who missed all of last season after 
injuring a knee while returning a kick in an exhibition game 
against the Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	At this point, Sehorn has already missed the Giants' first two  
exhibition games. There is no chance he will play this weekend 
against the Jets and only a slim shot he would play in the final 
game at Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe he would practice toward the end of that week for that  
one,'' Fassel said. ``Maybe then he can start practicing full time 
for the week of the Tampa game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sehorn was considered one of the best corners in the league  
before his knee injury. Conrad Hamilton stepped in last season and 
played very well, but Hamilton sprained an ankle in a scrimmage two 
weeks ago and he has been sidelined. 
</P>
<P>
	Fassel said Hamilton should be back in time for the season  
opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll start the guy who is most prepared at that time,'' Fassel  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillippi Sparks and Jeremy Lincoln have started at the corners  
in the preseason, but Lincoln struggled in Saturday night's 27-20 
win over Jacksonville. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
