<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Twist To Miss Hockey Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Former St. Louis Blues forward Tony Twist -- one  
of NHL's top enforcers -- says injuries from a motorcycle accident 
will sideline him for this season and possibly longer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Best-case scenario is for Twist to return to hockey in nine  
months. But he could be out 14 months or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``The knee thing is a lot more serious than I thought at  
first,'' said Twist, who is recuperating at his home in west St. 
Louis County. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old left wing was hurt Aug. 9 when his motorcycle  
rammed a car that cut him off in suburban Creve Coeur. The other 
motorist was cited for failure to yield and driving with a revoked 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist had a broken and dislocated pelvis, broken toe and bruised  
left knee. The critical issue was internal bleeding that threatened 
his life, delayed pelvis surgery for nearly four days and pushed a 
detailed knee exam back a week. 
</P>
<P>
	After surgery to insert a plate into the left side of his  
pelvis, Twist had a magnetic resonance imaging test last weekend on 
his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	It showed tears in both the posterior cruciate and lateral  
collateral ligaments. Instead of missing three to five months with 
his pelvis injury, Twist will be out an extra six to nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist's contract with the Blues expired June 30. An unrestricted  
free agent, he was still negotiating with other NHL teams when he 
was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Twist insisted that he will play again after sitting out next  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know where or when, but I'll be back,'' said the  
6-foot-2, 240-pound player. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
