<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Aug. 22, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Residents Evacuate As Bret Hits  
</P>
<P>
	CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) -- Hurricane Bret, the biggest storm  
to hit Texas in nearly 20 years, roared ashore today with 
horizontal sheets of rain and 125-mph winds that whipped and bent 
palm trees and forced thousands of people to flee inland. The 
rapidly developing storm made landfall about 6 p.m. in sparsely 
populated Kenedy County, about 70 miles south of Corpus Christi. 
Businesses and homes were shuttered from Brownsville to north of 
Corpus Christi, and highways leading inland were packed with 
bumper-to-bumper traffic for miles. 

</P>
<P>
	Many Rescue Crews Frustrated in Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	IZMIT, Turkey (AP) -- Thousands of rescue and medical crews raced  
to Turkey to help in the aftermath of the devastating earthquake, 
but in the sweeping chaos some relief units were sent to areas 
where there was no need -- while other regions needed more help. At 
the same time, Turkey's officials have been swamped with too much 
aid and saddled with rescue crews that have nothing to do because 
most of the injured have already been treated. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Die and Hundreds Injured in Plane Fire  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- A China Airlines jet burst into flames, flipped  
upside down and slid down the runway at Hong Kong's new airport 
today while trying to land in a tropical storm, killing two people 
and injuring at least 206, officials said. The crash was a major 
setback for the airline, which has struggled in recent years to 
overcome a poor safety record and a reputation for arrogant and 
undisciplined pilots. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Jets Retaliate in Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes attacked suspected  
guerrilla hideouts in southern Lebanon today, hours after two 
Israeli soldiers were wounded in an attack, Lebanese security 
officials said. Israeli jets fired two missiles at guerrilla 
positions in a region that faces Rihan, a village in the 
Israeli-occupied zone, the officials said on condition of 
anonymity. The area is about nine miles north of Israel's border. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat Eyes US Aid in Israel Impasse  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- With his envoys about to head to Washington,  
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat urged the United States today to 
step in to break the latest deadlock in the peace process with 
Israel. Arafat's call was quickly rejected by the administration of 
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who last month won assurances 
from President Clinton that Washington would avoid the direct role 
it has taken in the past. In a series of direct talks, Israeli and 
Palestinian negotiators have been unable to work out how to 
implement the Wye peace deal brokered by President Clinton in 
October. 

</P>
<P>
	Unusual Requirement for Mexico Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Pregnancy testing remains a common  
requirement in Mexico for women seeking jobs, whether in factories 
or executive suites, even though the government says it's illegal 
and human rights groups call it an invasion of privacy. Few Mexican 
women complain about the testing. In a nation where help-wanted 
postings frequently specify the required age, sex, marital status 
and ``appearance'' of would-be applicants, workers are little 
accustomed to insisting on their privacy or their rights. 

</P>
<P>
	Free Postage Exchanged for Profile  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Postage4Free.com Inc. plans to give Web surfers  
free, pre-stamped envelopes in exchange for giving their consumer 
profile -- including income level and what kind of car they drive -- 
to allow sponsors to target advertising and coupons on those 
envelopes based on that person's tastes. The South Florida company, 
a six-person operation founded this year, kicks off its Web site 
tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	'Sixth Sense' No. 1 for Third Week  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sixth Sense'' -- the supernatural  
thriller starring Bruce Willis as a therapist treating a boy who 
sees dead people -- has spooked $24.1 million out of moviegoers at 
the weekend box office, according to industry estimates today. It 
is the first film since the ``Phantom Menace'' to hold the No. 1 
spot for three consecutive weeks, grossing a total of $107.7 
million. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Reaches 50 Homers Again  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mark McGwire hit two home runs against the New  
York Mets today to become the first player to reach 50 homers in a 
season for four straight years. McGwire's 50th came on a 1-0 count 
leading off the seventh inning against Jeff Tam. The ball just 
cleared the outstretched glove of Shawon Dunston in left-center and 
landed just past the 396-foot sign. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants Beat Brewers 7-3 in Three-Game Sweep  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Barry Bonds, Jeff Kent and Ellis Burks  
connected for consecutive homers in the first inning today -- the 
second time in three days San Francisco hit three in a row -- and 
the Giants defeated Milwaukee 7-3. Kent homered in his first at-bat 
since coming off the disabled list as the Giants completed a 
three-game sweep. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
