<HEADLINE> Amateur Champ Chosen for Walker Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FAR HILLS, N.J. (AP) -- David Gossett, who won the U.S. Amateur  
on Sunday, and Hunter Haas, who lost in the semifinals, were among 
the final five players chosen for the 10-man team that will 
represent the United States in the Walker Cup next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Golf Association had already selected the first five  
players that will compete in the matches against amateurs from 
Great Britain and Ireland at Nairn Golf Club in Nairn, Scotland, on 
Sept. 11-12. 
</P>
<P>
	Those players, announced in July, were 1997 U.S. Amateur  
champion Matt Kuchar, 22, of Lake Mary, Fla.; 1998 runner-up Tom 
McKnight, 45, of Galax, Va.; Jonathan Byrd, 21, of Columbia, S.C.; 
Tim Jackson, 40, of Germantown, Tenn.; and Edward Loar, 21, of 
Rockwall, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Gossett, 20, of Germantown, Tenn., and Haas, 22,  
of Norman, Okla., those selected Sunday were John ``Spider'' 
Miller, 49, of Bloomington, Ind.; Bryce Molder, 20, of Conway, 
Ark.; and Steve Scott, 22, of Coral Springs, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Yates, 49, of Atlanta, the 1992 Mid-Amateur champion who  
played on the 1989 and 1993 Walker Cup teams, is the captain. 
</P>
<P>
	Begun in 1922, the Walker Cup is held every two years,  
alternately in the United States and the Great 
Britain-Ireland-Scotland region. Four foursomes and eight singles 
matches are played each day, with a total of 24 points available. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States leads the series 31-4-1. The sides have split  
the last two matches, with Great Britain and Ireland winning 14-10 
in 1995 at Royal Porthcawl Golf Club in Porthcawl, Wales, and the 
United States winning 18-6 at Quaker Ridge Golf Club in Scarsdale, 
N.Y., in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
