<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barber Is New Queen of Heptathlon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- First, Eunice Barber wrapped a French flag  
around her shoulders. Then she thought about her roots and hoped 
peace would return to her native Sierra Leone. 
</P>
<P>
	Barber became a French citizen in February and gave her new  
country its first gold medal of the World Championships when she 
won the grueling two-day heptathlon on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wonderful,'' Barber said after winning the 800 meters,  
the last of the seven events. ``It's a victory for France, for the 
people who have supported me, for my club, but I also share it with 
with my family in Sierra Leone and I hope peace would return to my 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mother gave me a lot of courage in my career,'' she said,  
then called her sister on a borrowed cellular phone. 
</P>
<P>
	But the first congratulatory call on another borrowed phone had  
come from Dominique Dufour, a French diplomat who opened a track 
and field club in Freetown, the Sierra Leone capital, and 
effectively launched Barber's career by convincing her to join it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dominique, Dominique ...,'' a barefoot Barber screamed into  
the phone, jumping up and down. She was tired but unable to contain 
her joy in the hot Seville night. 
</P>
<P>
	Barber, 24, competed for Sierra Leone at the last two Olympics,  
finishing fifth in Atlanta in 1996 and was fourth at the 1995 
worlds. But she always trained in France and finally took French 
citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	As a child and young woman, Barber grew up playing at the  
stadium in Freetown, where her mother worked as a secretary. Barber 
ran, jumped and threw -- inevitably leading to a career in the 
multi-discipline event. 
</P>
<P>
	For fun, she and other girls danced and imitated Spice Girls to  
a rap rhythm. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, she was invited by the French Olympic Committee to  
visit the country that would later become her adopted nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Barber, who also holds the French long jump record at 23 feet,  
took charge of the heptathlon Saturday with personal bests in the 
100 hurdles and high jump and never looked back. She effectively 
sealed her victory with yet another personal best in the javelin 
Sunday, building up a huge lead heading into the 800. 
</P>
<P>
	With 6,861 points, she set the season's best total and a new  
French record, improving her old mark and personal best by more 
than 300 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Barber steamrolled over her chief rival, Denise Lewis of  
Britain, who collected 6,724 points for her second silver in as 
many world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghada Shouaa of Syria, the Olympic gold medalist who missed two  
seasons with a serious back injury, made a stunning comeback by 
edging defending champion Sabine Braun of Germany by three points 
for the bronze with 6,500. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
