<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- With a beach volleyball pit, a juggler on  
stilts and a semi-trailer filled with Sony PlayStations, the 
inaugural Target Grand Prix was part auto race, part carnival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great,'' said Paul Lanigan of Chicago. ``You've got to  
figure a quarter of the people couldn't care less, so it's good to 
have something else to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auto racing came back to Chicago for the first time in more than  
40 years Sunday. Though the city was the site of the first known 
car race in the United States on Nov. 28, 1895, there hasn't been a 
major race here since 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	Which partly explains the circus-like atmosphere at the Chicago  
Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It came off as an event, not just a race. The world doesn't  
need any more races. But an event ...,'' said Chip Ganassi, 
president of the speedway and co-owner of Target/Chip Gnassi 
Racing. 
</P>
<P>
	While true race fans wandered the infield checking out the cars,  
taking pictures of the drivers and gawking at the teams' huge 
transporters before the race, there were plenty of sideshows to 
entertain those who were only partly curious in racing. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Extreme Volleyball Professionals put on an  
exhibition in the middle of the infield. There was a tent where 
children could get their faces painted and temporary tattoos. 
Another tent had about a dozen video games, as well as the truck 
filled with PlayStations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice,'' said Judy Murnane of Burbank, Ill., a NASCAR fan  
attending her first CART race. ``You can move around and walk 
around instead of sitting in the seats all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OK, but what about the race? Great, fans said. The entire track  
could be seen from all but the bottom five rows of the grandstand, 
and there was a Jumbotron at the start line to give fans a better 
view. 
</P>
<P>
	The only complaint was about the track -- it's not long enough.  
With a one-mile oval, it's unlikely there will ever be a 500-mile 
race at the CMS. Sunday's race was 225 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chicago's been waiting for a track for a long time,'' said Gil  
Weeden, a Chicago fan who's gone to the Indianapolis 500 for the 
last 27 years. ``Now that we've finally got one, it should be 500 
miles.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CONTRACT EXTENDED:* PacWest Racing had a busy day Sunday -- and  
that was before the race even began. 
</P>
<P>
	The team announced a two-year contract extension for Mark  
Blundell, who finished 21st after starting in the middle of the 
first row at the Target Grand Prix. Blundell, who's in his fourth 
season with the team, has won three times in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	PacWest also announced that Motorola will continue its title  
sponsorship for two more seasons, with an option for a third year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to winning the championship next year,'' said  
Bruce McCaw, PacWest's president. ``No pressure, Mark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PacWest has a second car, and that driver and the equipment  
lineup will be announced before the Sept. 12 race in Monterey, 
Calif. Though Mauricio Gugelmin is the current driver, speculation 
has been that he'll be replaced by Roberto Moreno. Moreno drove 
Blundell's car after Blundell broke his collarbone May 4. He missed 
eight races, returning for the Detroit Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAR-GAZING:* So taking a curve at 90 mph isn't enough of a  
thrill for you? How about taking that curve with Paul Newman behind 
the wheel? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, that white-haired driver giving rides in the pace car  
Sunday afternoon really was Newman. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was fabulous!'' said Chris Bidwill, wife of track co-owner  
Charles Bidwill III. ``He was very nice. Very friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newman and Mario Andretti were celebrity drivers Sunday for PPG  
Motorsports pace car program. Rides with the actor and the former 
Indianapolis 500 winner were auctioned off for charity -- the high 
bid for a ride with Newman was $10,000 -- but the two stuck around 
afterward to give other rides. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidwill didn't know she'd be riding with Newman until he pulled  
up next to her in a blue Lexus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `The race cars go three times as fast and BOOM!'''  
she said. ``It was exciting and he went very fast. He's a very good 
driver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 500 rides were given over the week, said John Love, a  
spokesman for PPG Industries. PPG usually takes 11 of its 36 pace 
cars to each week's race, Love said, giving rides to corporate 
sponsors, guests and the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``Racing is something very few people get to experience. So if  
we can give people a little of the experience, it helps us all in 
the understanding and appreciation for the event,'' Love said. 
``It's especially important here at a new market.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UNSWEETENED:* The inaugural Target Grand Prix was missing only  
one thing: Walter Payton. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton, co-owner of Payton-Coyne Racing, had to sit out the  
first race in his adopted hometown in more than 40 years because he 
wasn't feeling well, said his partner, Dale Coyne. The NFL's 
all-time leading rusher has a rare liver disease and is awaiting a 
transplant. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's fair,'' Coyne said before Sunday's race.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
