<DOCNO> APW19990822.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 18:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wolford May Cause Steelers a Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Steelers' handling of retired  
offensive tackle Will Wolford's contract is being investigated by 
the NFL for possible salary cap violations and could subject them 
to a fine or the loss of draft picks, The Associated Press learned 
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelers president Dan Rooney acknowledged the Steelers turned  
themselves into the NFL after determining they may have violated 
salary cap restrictions, but he would not identify the player 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will confirm that we told the league that this may be a  
problem and we reported it,'' Rooney said Sunday night. ``They have 
it under investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers may have turned themselves in as early as three  
months ago, but did not comment until now because it was under 
league investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's between the players union and the NFL,'' Rooney said.  
``We are not saying anything about it. We're just saying we turned 
ourselves in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rooney said the Steelers do not consider it to be a ``serious  
violation'' and they do not have any idea if they will be 
disciplined. 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidentally, Rooney, one of the NFL's most powerful owners  
and the man largely responsible for ending two NFL strikes because 
of his influence with the players, serves on the NFL's labor 
council. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelers director of football operations Tom Donahoe also is  
regarded as one of the league's experts on salary cap management. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think we did anything too serious, but we felt it  
still deserved an investigation by them,'' Rooney said. ``We don't 
want to be breaking the rules. I'm on the labor council.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers were last fined by the NFL -- $25,000 -- for failing  
to make all of their players available for interviews before the 
Super Bowl in Tempe, Ariz., in January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	An NFL-assigned arbitrator will determine whether the Steelers  
are subject to a fine that CNN-SI reported could reach $2 million, 
or the possible loss of draft choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolford's 1999 contract had a cap value of $2.575 million. If  
the NFL determines that Wolford's contract should count against the 
Steelers' cap, they would be considerably over their cap and thus 
would be subject to a fine. 
</P>
<P>
	If the NFL finds that the Steelers violated the cap, it may be  
because Wolford tried to do the Steelers a favor by delaying his 
retirement as they weighed how to replace injured tackle Justin 
Strzelczyk, who reinjured his knee last spring and may miss the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolford, who played last season with a torn chest muscle, told  
friends in January that he would pass up a $2.1 million contract 
for this season and would retire. He held a retirement party at his 
Kentucky home a month later. 
</P>
<P>
	But Steelers coach Bill Cowher asked the former Pro Bowl lineman  
to reconsider and to return for at least one more season. Wolford 
previously accommodated Cowher last season by shifting from guard, 
his preferred position, to left tackle after John Jackson signed 
with the San Diego Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolford tore his chest muscle in the fourth game of the 1998  
season, missed two of the next three games and started the final 
eight, effectively playing with one arm for much of the season, he 
said later. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolford initially considered retiring before the 1998 season,  
when he injured his neck in a swimming pool accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after Wolford told the Steelers last winter that he wanted  
to retire, Cowher held out hope that he might return, if only to 
play on passing downs. His agent, Ralph Cindrich, said Wolford 
might be receptive to such an arrangement. 
</P>
<P>
	But after the Steelers signed former St. Louis Rams left tackle  
Wayne Gandy to a $14 million, four-year contract, they released 
Wolford a day later, on April 7. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the San Francisco 49ers confirmed that the NFL was  
looking into possible salary cap violations during the time Carmen 
Policy was the team's president and Dwight Clark was the general 
manager. Both have since gone to work for the Cleveland Browns. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN-SI reported the player involved was tight end Brent Jones,  
himself a former Steelers player. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
