<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Going Ahead With Thai Auto Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- When U.S. auto giant General Motors  
unveiled plans to build its Southeast Asian production center in 
Thailand less than three years ago, the sky seemed the limit for 
the regional car industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian economies were booming and the demand for swanky sedans  
was growing. Nothing looked like it could get in the way for 
another prize foreign investment deal for tigerish Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the financial crisis in 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	GM's plans to produce 100,000 vehicles a year at a $640 million  
new plant on Thailand's eastern seaboard were dashed, as the 
regional motor market plunged even faster than Asian currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the Thai economy showing some signs of recovery, GM is  
pressing ahead, albeit on a vastly smaller scale than first 
envisioned. The first vehicles are set to roll off the production 
line in May 2000, 16 months behind schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first the capacity was going to be 100,000 units per year,  
but due to the economic crisis, we scaled that down to 40,000 per 
year,'' Kantanit Sukontasap, vice-president for corporate affairs 
at GM (Thailand), told The Associated Press in a recent interview. 
</P>
<P>
	And fittingly enough, instead of churning out grand four-door  
sedans as everyone expected, the Thai plant will become GM's second 
factory for the more humble mini multipurpose vehicle, the Zafira. 
</P>
<P>
	Following its European launch in April, the middle-priced  
minivan has proved popular, with GM's plant in Germany unable to 
fill orders that have so far totaled over 40,000 units, Kantanit 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-seater model is set to retail at between $16,200 and  
$21,600, which GM hopes will undercut imported competition. 
</P>
<P>
	But only 15 percent of production from the Thai plant will be  
for the local market, with the rest destined for export to various 
parts of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	GM will be pushing very hard to sell the Zafira in Asia to  
expand its meager share of the Japanese-dominated market from less 
than 1 percent at the moment to some 10 percent within three years, 
Kantanit said. 
</P>
<P>
	He is hopeful that if the vehicle proves a success in the  
region, GM would expand its production in Thailand, to reach an 
annual capacity of 100,000 vehicles, as originally intended. 
</P>
<P>
	While the economic jury is still out on Thailand's prospects of  
sustained recovery, the U.S. firm, which has already invested $500 
million on the plant at Rayong, insists it is upbeat about the 
country's prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we are here and will be here for the long-term,''  
Kantanit said. ``We believe that the Thai economy will start to 
really take off next year and that will coincide with our start of 
commercial operations midyear 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plant is set for completion by 1999.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
