<DOCNO> APW19990822.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 13:19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brooks Happy To Dump Bachelorhood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Albert Brooks finally abandoned his bachelor's  
life at age 50. Now he's reaping the benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Life, in general, used to be very lonely,'' Brooks told The  
New York Times in a story published Sunday. The 
writer-actor-director married two years ago and now has a young 
son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see people who remain single and immerse themselves in their  
work, and I don't know how they do it. It's very important to be 
grounded somewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks latest film, ``The Muse,'' deals with an aging Hollywood  
writer trying to get the magic back in his career. Its creator 
credits home and family with doing that for him. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his newfound paternal bliss, the creative force behind  
such films as ``Lost in America,'' ``Defending Your Life,'' and 
``Mother'' still has his edge, especially when it comes to talking 
about a regular Hollywood nemesis: the studio executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Have you ever noticed how no executives' names are ever  
mentioned in a bad review?'' Brooks says. ``That would be a hell of 
a thing to do! Mention all of the executives involved! It would be 
like printing pictures of drunk drivers!'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
