<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 12:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Probes Pfizer, Hoechst Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Commission is has launched  
a routine antitrust inquiry into an agreement between U.S. drugs 
giant Pfizer Inc. and Germany's Hoechst Marion Roussel AG to 
cooperate in the manufacture and sale of inhalable insulin. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies formally filed the agreement for regulatory  
approval with the European Union executive agency July 29, 
according to a notice published Friday in the EU's Official 
Journal. All major mergers and joint-ventures impacting on markets 
within the 15-nation bloc require approval from the Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU called on interested parties to file their views within  
10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies in November announced an agreement to jointly  
construct an insulin production center in Frankfurt, Germany, and 
to couple their global sales and marketing resources to 
commercialize inhaled insulin that will reduce the reliance of 
diabetics on insulin injections. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
