</P>
<P>
	Miller was jubilant over her third straight personal best after  
finishing second at 10.79. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting there,'' she said. ``Marion's a great athlete, but  
she's not the only one. She's beatable. Everybody is beatable. 
She's not invincible. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be good for our sport that a lot of us are  
stepping up and it's not just going to be -- so, what about Marion 
Jones?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, Jones will be beatable, but she hasn't lost a sprint  
race in two years. She only appears vulnerable in the long jump, 
where she has lost three times. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's other finals, France's Eunice Barber won the  
heptathlon with a career-best 6,861 points and Germany's Karsten 
Kobs took the hammer throw at 263 feet, 3 inches. Kobs celebrated 
by running across the field and diving into the steeplechase water 
jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Michael Johnson, the three-time defending champion in  
the men's 400, eased through his opening-round heat in 45.35. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's 1,500 semifinals, the two fastest milers in  
history, Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco and Noah Ngeny of Kenya, won 
their heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Paraskevi Tsiamita had the longest women's triple jump of the  
year, 49-5 1/2, leading the way into the final. Inessa Kravets, the 
world record-holder from Ukraine, failed to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Svetlana Masterkova of Russia and former  
champion Maria Mutola of Mozambique were the semifinal winners in 
the women's 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic champion Lars Riedel, seeking his fifth consecutive  
world discus title, qualified for the final, but Virgilijus Alekna 
of Lithuania, ranked No. 1 in the world last year, led the 
qualifiers at 216-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamaica's Deon Hemmings, the 1996 Olympic gold medalist, ran the  
fastest time (54.27) in the heats of the women's 400 hurdles. 
Defending champion Nezha Bidouane of Morocco also advanced to the 
semifinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990822.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 18:59:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Swiss Secret Service Head Barred </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- The head of the Swiss secret service  
has been suspended over reports that he was involved in creating a 
secret army, the Swiss government announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense minister Adolf Ogi told reporters Peter Regli had been  
suspended at his own request as a fraud investigation took on 
``unimaginable'' dimensions. Regli denied the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Former defense ministry accountant Dino Bellasi was arrested  
last week accused of stealing $5.8 million from his employers, the 
largest embezzlement ever reported by the Swiss government. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was only after a newspaper report on Sunday that deputy  
federal prosecutor Felix Baenziger admitted that ``hundreds'' of 
weapons, as well as ammunition, had been seized from a site near 
the Swiss capital, Bern, in connection with the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the weapons had come from the Swiss army, Baenziger  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bellasi claimed that he had been acting under orders from Regli,  
his superior, who in 1994 ordered him to create a secret army, and 
had given him money to buy arms. 
</P>
<P>
	Regli told reporters the allegation was ``absurd'' and ``a  
tissue of lies.'' He said he believed Bellasi should undergo a 
psychiatric examination. 
</P>
<P>
	Ogi told reporters he still had confidence in Regli, but he  
retained the right to suspend other members of the secret service 
if he felt the investigation required it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bellasi, 39, is accused of obtaining the money over a five-year  
period in the form of advances to cover the costs of army exercises 
which never took place. The fraud came to light after Bellasi 
continued to submit claims even after he left his job in November 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested as he apparently tried to leave the country last  
week and is being held in custody. His wife, who was arrested with 
him, has been released. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990822.0101 </DOCNO>
