<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 13:31:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russians Discuss Battle Vs. Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's prime minister summoned defense and law  
enforcement chiefs Sunday to review their campaign against Islamic 
militants occupying southern villages -- a campaign that has failed 
to dislodge the rebels despite two weeks of attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting in Moscow came after Russian forces chalked up some  
victories in the republic of Dagestan. They said Sunday they 
captured parts of a rebel stronghold a day after seizing a key 
rebel supply route. 
</P>
<P>
	Control over the Tando mountaintop and the Kharami mountain pass  
leading to neighboring breakaway Chechnya is seen as vital for the 
militants. The strength of the Russian positions was unclear, and 
the tenacious rebels have recaptured ground before. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels crossed from Chechnya to seize several villages in  
Dagestan on Aug. 7. They are seeking an independent Muslim state in 
the Caucasus Mountains region. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting is the worst in Russia since federal troops  
withdrew in humiliation after a 1994-96 war with separatists in 
Chechnya. The Kremlin is pouring troops and weaponry into Dagestan 
but wants to avoid a repeat of the Chechnya debacle, particularly 
ahead of December parliamentary elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called an unusual meeting Sunday  
of Russia's ``power ministers'': Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev; 
Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo, in charge of the police force; 
the head of the Federal Security Service, the main successor to the 
KGB, Nikolai Petrushev; and the chief of the armed forces general 
staff, Gen. Anatoly Kvashnin. 
</P>
<P>
	They discussed strategy, specific military operations, Russia's  
political situation and aid to refugees, Russian news agencies 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has also appealed to the United States, Israel, Saudi  
Arabia and Turkey for intelligence on the rebels, Rushailo said on 
Russian television Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin -- a former national security chief who was named prime  
minister a week after this month's fighting began -- met later 
Sunday with the head of Dagestan, Magomedali Magomedov. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dagestan, federal troops were in partial control of Tando and  
were widening their grip on the area, Lt. Col. Viktor Gubriy of the 
Defense Ministry said from Dagestan's capital, Makhachkala. 
</P>
<P>
	The military command and Dagestan's Interior Ministry said 28  
guerrillas were killed in fighting Saturday over the Kharami pass, 
used to ferry fighters and weapons from Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of Russian casualties in the clashes Saturday and  
Sunday was unclear. The Defense Ministry reported one officer 
killed Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials say up to 700 rebels have been killed in the  
two-week conflict, though the rebels say the figure is hugely 
exaggerated. Moscow has acknowledged losing about 40 soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian commanders have been predicting the militants' imminent  
defeat for days, but the fighting has dragged on. President 
Yeltsin's spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin conceded Saturday, ``It's 
impossible to expect a quick solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is believed to have dispatched thousands of troops to  
fight the rebel force of about 1,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in Dagestan, an impoverished region west of the  
Caspian Sea, say more than 11,000 civilians have fled the remote, 
rugged conflict zone. While support for separatism in Chechnya was 
widespread, most people in Dagestan oppose the militants, and many 
Muslim leaders in Russia have also condemned the rebels' violent 
tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestani police are cracking down on Islamic extremists,  
detaining 100 people in the past 10 days and seizing religious 
literature in one home, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990822.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 13:31:15 </DATE_TIME>
