<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Agency Readies for Hurricane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hurricane Bret has the ``clear potential of  
producing a major disaster,'' possibly more destructive than 
Hurricane Andrew in 1992, the National Weather Service declared 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A vital difference between Bret and Andrew, the service's Jim  
Hoke said, is that the hurricane bearing down on the Texas east 
coast is moving much slower while carrying the same 140 mph winds. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoke appeared with officials of the Federal Emergency Management  
Agency to discuss preparations for the expected afternoon or 
evening landfall. 
</P>
<P>
	FEMA's director of response and recovery operations, Bruce  
Bahghman, said the agency has prepared four emergency medical and 
relief teams for deployment once the location of Bret's landfall is 
certain. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoke said a tornado watch was to be issued Sunday afternoon on  
the south Texas coast to warn against twisters Bret was likely to 
spawn as it closed in between Corpus Christi and Brownsville. The 
area already was under a hurricane warning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hurricane Bret has the clear potential of producing a major  
disaster,'' Hoke said. ``It has the ingredients to threaten life 
and property in many ways. These ways include storm surge, flooding 
from rains, high winds and tornadoes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the biggest worry of emergency workers is that barrier  
islands and low-lying coastal areas will be inundated by a storm 
surge of 10-15 feet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990822.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-22 15:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greene Just Misses World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- The track was lightning fast, and so were  
Maurice Greene and Marion Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene overcame a stumbling start to win his second straight  
world title at 100 meters Sunday night, missing his world record by 
.01 seconds with a time of 9.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones kept the gold medal run going in her family, matching the  
victory of her husband, shot putter C.J. Hunter on Saturday, in 
winning her second consecutive women's 100 in 10.70. Her time 
equaled the sixth fastest in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe if I didn't stumble, my time would have been  
faster,'' Greene said after halfway completing his goal of sweeping 
the 100 and 200 at the World Championships, a feat not accomplished 
in a major international championship since Carl Lewis at the 1984 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``The beginning was very shaky, but I didn't panic. I ran under  
control. I finished strong,'' he said. ``In the 100, everything you 
do takes off hundredths of a second. I wasn't trying for the world 
record. I don't try anymore. If it comes, it comes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as he crossed the finish line, Greene celebrated by  
twirling his hand to the crowd. After seeing his time on the 
scoreboard, he shook his head and said, ``Damn,'' realizing how 
close he had come to matching the world record of 9.79 he set at 
Athens June 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene kneeled on the track, holding his head in his hands for  
several seconds. Then he looked up at training partner Ato Boldon 
in the stands and shouted, ``That's for you, Ato,'' before setting 
out on a victory lap with the American flag. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, who pulled out of the championships with an injury, and  
hurdler Larry Wade embraced Greene on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach John Smith, who has molded Greene into the world's top  
sprinter, was impressed by the way his protege ran down Canada's 
Bruny Surin over the final 20 meters. Surin finished second in 
9.84, equaling the third fastest time ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``He won it coming from behind -- Carl Lewis style,'' Smith said.  
</P>
<P>
	Greene was relieved that he had won one of his toughest races.  
</P>
<P>
	``In the end I was just thinking I'm glad it's all over,'' he  
said. ``I think Bruny and I produced a great spectacle, maybe one 
of the best ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surin blamed himself for the loss.  
</P>
<P>
	``That was very close,'' he said. ``I knew I could beat him, but  
I made a mistake. I passed him a little and panicked. I got excited 
too soon instead of staying relaxed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, one of Greene's training partners, wasn't surprised at  
the comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's caught me so many times,'' said Boldon, the 1997 200  
world champion. ``When he puts his head down ... that's what 
carries him through the finish line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew he was going to catch Bruny. Bruny has a tendency to  
put his head up. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is having the best season ever by a sprinter. He's run  
9.79, 9.80, 9.85, 9.87 and 9.91 (twice). Without the stumble, he 
would have run 9.78.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. team coach George Williams also praised Greene's effort.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought he ran a great race except for the first step,''  
Williams said. ``He stuttered. That cost him a world record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones didn't come close to a world record -- Florence Griffth  
Joyner's 10.49 -- but she did run the world's fastest time of 1999 
and broke the championship record of 10.76 she set in Saturday's 
quarterfinals. Only Jones and Griffith Joyner ever have run faster 
than 10.72 -- FloJo four times and Jones seven. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, Jones was not the fastest out of the blocks, but she  
quickly assumed control and ran her usual powerful race, beating 
Inger Miller by just over a meter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming off the victory by C.J. last night, I'm very excited to  
win,'' the ebullient Jones said. ``The goal for the week was to get 
five gold medals in the family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter, who began the gold rush, roared from the stands after  
his wife's victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones will have to do the rest of the family work. She is  
seeking an unprecedented four golds -- in the 100, 200, long jump 
and a relay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I nailed my start today, ...'' Jones said. ``That was perhaps  
the reason I pulled off the victory. I knew that Inger was running 
extra fast. But I put it all together and executed my race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was jubilant over her third straight personal best after  
finishing second at 10.79. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm getting there,'' she said. ``Marion's a great athlete, but  
she's not the only one. She's beatable. Everybody is beatable. 
She's not invincible. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be good for our sport that a lot of us are  
stepping up and it's not just going to be -- so, what about Marion 
Jones?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, Jones will be beatable, but she hasn't lost a sprint  
race in two years. She only appears vulnerable in the long jump, 
where she has lost three times. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's other finals, France's Eunice Barber won the  
heptathlon with a career-best 6,861 points and Germany's Karsten 
Kobs took the hammer throw at 263 feet, 3 inches. Kobs celebrated 
by running across the field and diving into the steeplechase water 
jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Michael Johnson, the three-time defending champion in  
the men's 400, eased through his opening-round heat in 45.35. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's 1,500 semifinals, the two fastest milers in  
history, Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco and Noah Ngeny of Kenya, won 
their heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Paraskevi Tsiamita had the longest women's triple jump of the  
year, 49-5 1/2, leading the way into the final. Inessa Kravets, the 
world record-holder from Ukraine, failed to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Svetlana Masterkova of Russia and former  
champion Maria Mutola of Mozambique were the semifinal winners in 
the women's 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic champion Lars Riedel, seeking his fifth consecutive  
world discus title, qualified for the final, but Virgilijus Alekna 
of Lithuania, ranked No. 1 in the world last year, led the 
qualifiers at 216-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamaica's Deon Hemmings, the 1996 Olympic gold medalist, ran the  
fastest time (54.27) in the heats of the women's 400 hurdles. 
Defending champion Nezha Bidouane of Morocco also advanced to the 
semifinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
